{{if .Beads}}## Beads

- Use `br ready --json` to find work.
- Use `br list --json` to inspect the full issue graph.
- Use `br update <id> --status in_progress` when claiming work.
- Use `br close <id> --reason "..."`
- Run `br sync --flush-only` before committing `.beads/` changes.
- Close delivery beads through the Burpvalve gate so the bead close, `.beads/issues.jsonl`, verifier evidence, attestation, and commit describe the same staged payload. Admin-only `.beads/` housekeeping may batch when no delivery payload is staged.
- `br dep cycles` must be empty.
- Never run bare `bv`; use robot flags such as `bv --robot-triage`, `bv --robot-next`, or `bv --robot-insights`.

{{end}}## Taking Orders And Handoffs

- Treat owner, maintainer, and active orchestrator assignments as scoped work orders. If the instruction conflicts with this file or tracked decisions, stop and ask for the smallest ruling that unblocks the work.
{{if .Beads}}- Claim the bead before implementation, keep status current, and use the bead id in coordination messages, reservations, verifier packets, and close reasons.
{{end}}- Announce shared-file scope before editing files that other active agents may touch. Reserve only the paths you intend to change and release reservations promptly when you hand off or stop.
- Do not widen unclear requirements into adjacent features, cleanup, or refactors. Record blockers and decisions in the durable place named for this repo.

## Atomic Work And Commits

- One feature{{if .Beads}}, one bead{{end}}, one commit.
- One bug, one fix, one commit.
- Do not combine two features, two fixes, or a feature plus a fix in the same commit.
- When git committing, never add co-authorship for Codex or Claude (no Co-Authored-By trailers for AI tools). Author is clicksopendoors only.
- Never estimate or reference development time or timelines. Describe scope, sequencing, and blockers instead.
